post_text:
Meeting of Waters, Brazil
This is the confluence between the dark Rio Negro river and the pale sandy coloured Amazon River (this stretch of the river is called Solimoes River) in Brazil. For around 6 km the waters of the river run parallel to each other without mixing. The Meeting of Waters is a major tourist attraction in the country. The Rio Negro’s dark waters are due to decaying vegetation from sandy clearings. The two rivers have different temperatures, speeds, and densities that prevent their waters from mixing but they are a spectacle to behold!

Image credit: James Davis Photography/Shutterstock

Lake Hillier: This extraordinary lake is located in the Recherche Archipelago of Australia. From the top, its striking bubble gum pink color is unmissable! Till date, the exact reason of the color remains unexplained. Theories abound, however. The dominant one mentions about a combination of high salt content and certain species of microbes living in the lake contributing to its pink color. The island where it is located is out of bound for tourists who can only enjoy its beauty via helicopter rides. Only researchers with special permission are allowed on the island.
Image credit: Matteo_it/Shutterstock

post_text:
The Crooked Forest

Near the town of Gryfino in Poland you will find a grove of 400 pine trees with very odd shapes. Together they constitute the Crooked Forest. These trees exhibit an almost 90 degree bend from their base in the northern direction and after growing for around 3 to 9 feet in that direction, they again curve upwards and grow towards the sky. This unique shape of these trees is yet to be explained by science. Many theories have been put forward like the existence of some unique natural force in the area to intentional manipulations done by farmers when planting the trees. However, as the nearby settlements were abandoned during the World War 2 and these trees were possibly planted in the 1930s, no one remained to explain their unique shape. People are back in the region now and you can visit this beautiful grove and admire the Crooked Forest if you happen to visit Poland in the future

Activists and environmentalists have tried to prevent further destruction to the rainforest and protect the Indigenous peoples living there. However, their activism has made them a target of groups wanting access to the land. According to the reports, on average, one activist has been killed in Brazil every week since 2002. Most of the killings happened in remote areas of the Amazon.

post_text:
The world’s largest mirror!
One of the world’s extreme vistas, the Salar de Uyuni of Bolivia is the world’s largest salt flat. A prehistoric lake that evaporated left behind this massive salt flat stretching for over 4,050 square miles of the Altiplano. A thick crust of salt covers the entire landscape here. But the most magical part is when at certain times of the year, the surrounding lakes overflow and a thin layer of water covers the salt flat. You have the world’s largest mirror then! The entire salt flat reflects the vast blue sky and you can imagine how surreal that would look! The Salar de Uyuni is also of great commercial significance as salt and lithium are extracted in vast amounts at the site. The world’s first salt hotel is also located here.

Image credit: Shutterstock.com

post_text: Latin America has seen its fair share of conflict. Outside of real, active official war zones, Latin America is considered to be the most violent region in the world. How much violence is taking place varies from country to country. Overall, however, there is a lot of bloodshed. In 2016, there were about 400 murders taking place each day, adding up to about ⅓ of all homicides on Earth. To put that in context, Latin America is home to just 8% of the world’s population.

In this defensive position, the legs and other delicate appendages of the animal is withdrawn inside the rolled up body which is usually protected by scales, spines, or tough skin. Here are some pics of awesome animals that exhibit volvation:
1. Short beaked echidna
2. Two lesser hedgehog tenrecs
3. Lion cubs playing with a rolled up pangolin

post_text:
Myth Buster:
What most of us know: Siberian tigers are the largest tiger subspecies.

Truth: As per WCS Russia and Panthera, the average Siberian tiger is nearly the same size as the average Bengal tiger. The accounts of massive Siberian tigers weighing as much as 660 pounds mostly come from stories of hunters around 100 years back but there is not enough evidence to substantiate such claims.

However, when winter comes , the Siberian tigers develop a thick, fluffy fur that definitely will give complex to the Bengals!

So. Siberian tigers are not the largest but the fluffiest!!

Image credit: Shutterstock.com
